    "ragtruth_id": "114",
    "text": "Richard Dysart, the actor who portrayed the character Leland McKenzie on NBC’s drama \"L.A. Law,\" died on Sunday at his home in Santa Monica, California, after a long illness, his wife, artist Kathryn Jacobi, announced. He was 86. Dysart was nominated for the Emmy for outstanding supporting actor in a drama series for four straight years, finally winning the trophy in 1992. He was one of the few actors to appear in every episode of the show, which aired for eight seasons from 1986 to 1994. Dysart also had a notable career in film, playing a variety of authority figures. He portrayed Harry Truman in two telefilms, and also played Secretary of War Henry L. Stimson and J. Edgar Hoover. In addition, he had roles in \"The Thing,\" \"The Terminal Man,\" \"The Falcon and the Snowman,\" \"Warning Sign,\" \"Pale Rider,\" and \"Wall Street,\" among others. Dysart was born March 30, 1929, in Boston, and raised in Maine. He graduated from Emerson College with a master's degree in speech communications and initially pursued a career in radio before being tempted by acting. He later joined the American Conservatory Theater and toured the country doing plays before landing his first roles on Broadway.",
