    "ragtruth_id": "115",
    "text": "Emmy-winning actor Richard Dysart has passed away at the age of 86. Dysart was best known for his role as Leland McKenzie in the long-running NBC drama \"L.A. Law\". He played the cranky senior partner of the law firm McKenzie, Brackman, Chaney and Kuzak for eight seasons from 1986 to 1994. Dysart was nominated for an Emmy for outstanding supporting actor in a drama series for four consecutive years and finally won the award in 1992. He was one of the few actors to appear in every episode of the show. Dysart's career also included roles in Broadway productions and numerous films and television shows. He played Coach in the original 1972 Broadway production of \"That Championship Season\" and portrayed J. Edgar Hoover in the 1993 USA telefilm \"Marilyn & Bobby: Her Final Affair\". Dysart's range of authority-figure parts extended to playing Harry Truman in the CBS telefilm \"Day One\" and the Secretary of Defense in \"Meteor\" (1979). He also had a talent for playing doctors, with notable roles in movies such as \"The Hospital\" (1971) and \"Being There\" (1979). Dysart was born in Boston and raised in Maine. He attended Emerson College and initially pursued a career in radio before turning to acting. Dysart's last onscreen appearance was in the 2002 \"L.A. Law\" reunion telefilm. He is survived by his wife, stepson, daughter-in-law, mother-in-law, brother, sister-in-law, and grandchildren. A private memorial is being planned.",
